{"title_page": "Sydenham railway station (London)", "text_new": "{{For|other stations called Sydenham|Sydenham railway station (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Sydenham (London)\n| image_name    = Sydenham station main building June 2010.JPG\n| manager       = [[London Overground]]\n| owner         = [[Network Rail]]\n| fare_zone     = 3\n| locale        = [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]]\n| borough       = [[London Borough of Lewisham]]\n| years1        = 5 June 1839\n| events1       = Opened by the [[London and Croydon Railway]]\n| years2        = 1844\n| events2       = Croydon platform re-sited\n| years3        = 1982\n| events3       = London platform re-sited\n| years4        = 23 May 2010\n| events4       = [[East London Line]] started<ref name=\"Sydenham Town\">{{cite web| url=http://sydenham.org.uk/news_railway_09_09.html| website=Sydenham Town| title=News: Sydenham Rail Users Meeting| date=17 September 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007123205/http://sydenham.org.uk:80/news_railway_09_09.html| archivedate=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n| symbol        = overground\n| symbol2       = rail\n| platforms     = 2\n<!--\n| railexits0405 = {{increase}} 1.586\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 1.544\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 2.139\n| railexits0708 = {{increase}} 2.317\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 2.222\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 2.162\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 2.582\n| railexits1112 = {{increase}} 2.993\n| railexits1213 = {{increase}} 3.191\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 3.296 -->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 3.400\n| railexits1516 = {{increase}} 4.066\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 4.282\n| railexits1718 = {{decrease}} 4.148\n| railexits1819 = {{increase}} 4.265\n| railcode      = SYD\n| access        = Yes\n| access_note   = <ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/london-overground-network-map.pdf| title=London Overground system map| publisher=Transport for London| date=May 2018}}</ref>\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.4254|-0.0544|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| dft_category  = D\n}}\n\n'''Sydenham (London)''' is a railway station in [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] in the [[London Borough of Lewisham]], South London. Originally opened in 1839, the station is located on the former [[Croydon Canal]], which is now a branch of the [[Brighton Main Line]], often known as the Sydenham Corridor. Sydenham falls within [[Travelcard Zone 3]] and is served by [[London Overground]] and [[Southern (Govia Thameslink Railway)|Southern]]. The station is {{miles-chains|6|mi|32|chain|km}} down the line from {{stn|London Bridge}}.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Croydon, Norwood & Woodside RJD 53.jpg|thumb|left|A 1908 [[Railway Clearing House]] map of lines around the [[Brighton Main Line]] between South Croydon and Selhurst / Forest Hill, as well as surrounding lines]]\n\nThe Croydon Canal opened in 1809 linking the [[Grand Surrey Canal]] to [[Croydon]], however the waterway was never successful, and in 1836, it was the first canal to be abandoned by an [[Act of Parliament]]. The alignment was purchased by the [[London and Croydon Railway]], who drained the canal and re-opened as a railway on the 5 June 1839. In 1844, L&CR was given authority to test the first [[atmospheric railway]] equipment between Dartmouth Arms (now Forest Hill) and West Croydon.<ref>{{Cite book| last= Turner | first= John Howard | year=1978 | title= The London Brighton and South Coast Railway 1 Origins and Formation| publisher=[[Batsford]] | isbn= 0-7134-0275-X |page=250 }}</ref> In 1846, the railway became part of the [[London, Brighton and South Coast Railway]] and in the following year, the system was abandoned. The station was originally built south of Sydenham Road (A212) however, due to the construction of the branch to Crystal Palace in 1852, platform 2 was resited to its current position.<ref>{{Cite book| last= Turner | first= John Howard | year=1978 | title= The London Brighton and South Coast Railway 2 Establishment and Growth | publisher=[[Batsford]] | isbn= 0-7134-1198-8 |pages=41\u201345 }}</ref> Platform 1 and its station building remained south of the road bridge, until 1982 when [[British Rail]] decided to construct a replacement platform 90 meters north, parallel to Peak Hill Gardens due to the retaining wall beginning to collapse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydenhamsociety.com/2011/09/sydenham-station-one-of-best-preserved-on-line/|title = Sydenham Station one of best preserved on line|publisher=Sydenham Society|year=2011|accessdate =21 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Big Four (British railway companies)|Big Four grouping]] led to [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway (SR)]] management until nationalistation in 1948. Between 1948 and 1982 Sydenham was part of the [[Southern Region of British Railways|Southern Region]] and following sectorisation, until privatisation, Sydenham became part of the [[Network SouthEast]] sector. Upon privatisation in May 1996, the station management passed to [[Connex South Central]]. Connex was stripped of the franchise due to poor financial management and in 2001, Govia South Central (Southern) took over the franchise and management of the station. Southern remained the sole train provider until 2010, when London Overground took over management of the station and began running trains as part of the [[East London Line]] extension.\n\nSydenham was the first station to serve the area, however, there are, or have been, five other stations in the Sydenham:\n* {{Stnlnk|Lower Sydenham}} on the [[Hayes Line]]\n* {{Stnlnk|Upper Sydenham}} on the now closed [[Crystal Palace railway station|Crystal Palace (High Level) line]]\n* {{Stnlnk|Sydenham Hill}}, {{Stnlnk|Penge East}} on the {{LUL stations|station=Victoria}} to [[Orpington]] line.\n\n==Station layout==\nLike all intermediate stations between New Cross Gate and Norwood Junction, Sydenham has two platforms, facing two (up and down slow) of the four tracks with the two fast tracks run between the two slow lines. There are three entrances - the ticket office on platform 2 from Sydenham Station Approach, entrance on platform 1 from Peak Hill Gardens and a gate on platform 2 which is not unlocked regularly. A locally owned small cafe named ''On The Hoof'' which also has locations at other stations on the line, is in the main station building.\n\n==Services==\n{{London Overground East London Line |width=360px |collapse=yes }}\n\nSydenham is served by 8 trains in each direction off peak, with additional Southern services at peak hours. London Overground operates 5 car trains while Southern operates 4-10 car trains throughout the day.\n\nOff Peak frequencies are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Platform\n! Frequency<br>(per hour)\n! Destination\n! Service Pattern\n! Operator\n! Line\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 1\n|rowspan=3| 4\n| [[Highbury & Islington station|Highbury & Islington]]\n|rowspan=2| All stations via<br> {{rws|Shoreditch High Street}}<ref name=\"ELL Times\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/highbury-islington-to-west-croydon-and-clapham-junction-timetable-may-2013.pdf| title = East & Inner South London Line timetable| publisher=[[Transport for London]]| year=2013| accessdate =26 August 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023011137/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/highbury-islington-to-west-croydon-and-clapham-junction-timetable-may-2013.pdf| archivedate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|- \n| {{rws|Dalston Junction}}\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n| [[London Bridge station|London Bridge]]\n| All stations<ref name=\"SN Metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/plan-your-journey/timetables/|title = Southern timetables|publisher=Southern|year=2013|accessdate =26 August 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815144833/http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/plan-your-journey/timetables/| archivedate=15 August 2013}}</ref>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''      \n|-\n|rowspan=6| 2\n|rowspan=2| 4\n| {{rws|Crystal Palace}}\n| Next station<ref name=\"ELL Times\"/>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n| [[West Croydon station|West Croydon]]\n| All stations<ref name=\"ELL Times\"/>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2\n| [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]]<br> (Mon-Sat)\n| All stations via {{rws|Clapham Junction}}<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| {{rws|Caterham}} (Mon-Sat)\n| All stations via [[East Croydon station|East Croydon]]<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| [[West Croydon station|West Croydon]]<br> (Peaks & Sun only)\n| Fast to {{rws|Norwood Junction}}<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| {{rws|Tattenham Corner}}<br> (Sun only)\n| All stations via [[East Croydon station|East Croydon]]<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|}\n\n==Connections==\n[[London Buses]] routes [[London Buses route 122|122]], [[London Buses route 176|176]],  [[London Buses route 197|197]], [[London Buses route 202|202]] and [[London Buses route 450|450]] serve the station. While routes [[London Buses route 75|75]] and [[London Buses route 194|194]] run close by.\n\n==Lines==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rail|title=LOG}}\n{{s-line|system=LOG|line=East London|previous=Forest Hill|next=Crystal Palace|type=One|type2=Three|rowsmid=2|rows1=2}}\n{{s-line|system=LOG|line=East London|previous=Forest Hill|next=Penge West|type=One|type2=Four|hidemid=yes|hide1=yes}}\n{{rail insert}}\n{{rail line one to two|previous={{Stnlnk|Forest Hill}}|next1={{Stnlnk|Crystal Palace}}|next2={{Stnlnk|Penge West}} or {{stnlnk|Norwood Junction}}||route1=[[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]]<br><small>[[Crystal Palace Line]]|route2=[[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]]<br><small>[[Brighton Main Line]]|col=A7CE38}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sydenham railway station (London)}}\n*[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/SYD/details.html National Rail: Sydenham (SYD)]\n*[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/sjp/SYD/stationOverview.xhtml National Rail: Sydenham station plan]\n*[http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/station-information/SYD/ Southern: Sydenham page]\n*[http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/live-running-information/SYD/departures/ Southern:  Live departures, Sydenham]\n*{{gbmaprim|TQ3530071611|Maps and aerial photos}}\n\n{{Transport in London}}\n{{TSGN and SE Stations|Outer South=y|Caterham=y|FCC None=y|SE None=y}}\n{{London Overground navbox|Serving=y|ELL=y}}\n{{UK railway stations}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in the London Borough of Lewisham]]\n[[Category:Former London, Brighton and South Coast Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1839]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by London Overground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Southern]]\n[[Category:Sydenham, London]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other stations called Sydenham|Sydenham railway station (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Sydenham (London)\n| image_name    = Sydenham station main building June 2010.JPG\n| manager       = [[London Overground]]\n| owner         = [[Network Rail]]\n| fare_zone     = 3\n| locale        = [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]]\n| borough       = [[London Borough of Lewisham]]\n| years1        = 5 June 1839\n| events1       = Opened by the [[London and Croydon Railway]]\n| years2        = 1844\n| events2       = Croydon platform re-sited\n| years3        = 1982\n| events3       = London platform re-sited\n| years4        = 23 May 2010\n| events4       = [[East London Line]] started<ref name=\"Sydenham Town\">{{cite web| url=http://sydenham.org.uk/news_railway_09_09.html| website=Sydenham Town| title=News: Sydenham Rail Users Meeting| date=17 September 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007123205/http://sydenham.org.uk:80/news_railway_09_09.html| archivedate=7 October 2009}}</ref>\n| symbol        = overground\n| symbol2       = rail\n| platforms     = 2\n<!--\n| railexits0405 = {{increase}} 1.586\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 1.544\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 2.139\n| railexits0708 = {{increase}} 2.317\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 2.222\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 2.162\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 2.582\n| railexits1112 = {{increase}} 2.993\n| railexits1213 = {{increase}} 3.191\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 3.296 -->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 3.400\n| railexits1516 = {{increase}} 4.066\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 4.282\n| railexits1718 = {{decrease}} 4.148\n| railexits1819 = {{increase}} 4.265\n| railcode      = SYD\n| access        = Yes\n| access_note   = <ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/london-overground-network-map.pdf| title=London Overground system map| publisher=Transport for London| date=May 2018}}</ref>\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.4254|-0.0544|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| dft_category  = D\n}}\n\n'''Sydenham (London)''' is a railway station in [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] in the [[London Borough of Lewisham]], South London. Originally opened in 1839, the station is located on the former [[Croydon Canal]], which is now a branch of the [[Brighton Main Line]], often known as the Sydenham Corridor. Sydenham falls within [[Travelcard Zone 3]] and is served by [[London Overground]] and [[Southern (Govia Thameslink Railway)|Southern]]. The station is {{miles-chains|6|mi|32|chain|km}} down the line from {{stn|London Bridge}}.\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Croydon, Norwood & Woodside RJD 53.jpg|thumb|left|A 1908 [[Railway Clearing House]] map of lines around the [[Brighton Main Line]] between South Croydon and Selhurst / Forest Hill, as well as surrounding lines]]\n\nThe Croydon Canal opened in 1809 linking the [[Grand Surrey Canal]] to [[Croydon]], however the waterway was never successful, and in 1836, it was the first canal to be abandoned by an [[Act of Parliament]]. The alignment was purchased by the [[London and Croydon Railway]], who drained the canal and re-opened as a railway on the 5 June 1839. In 1844, L&CR was given authority to test the first [[atmospheric railway]] equipment between Dartmouth Arms (now Forest Hill) and West Croydon.<ref>{{Cite book| last= Turner | first= John Howard | year=1978 | title= The London Brighton and South Coast Railway 1 Origins and Formation| publisher=[[Batsford]] | isbn= 0-7134-0275-X |page=250 }}</ref> In 1846, the railway became part of the [[London, Brighton and South Coast Railway]] and in the following year, the system was abandoned. The station was originally built south of Sydenham Road (A212) however, due to the construction of the branch to Crystal Palace in 1852, platform 2 was resited to its current position.<ref>{{Cite book| last= Turner | first= John Howard | year=1978 | title= The London Brighton and South Coast Railway 2 Establishment and Growth | publisher=[[Batsford]] | isbn= 0-7134-1198-8 |pages=41\u201345 }}</ref> Platform 1 and its station building remained south of the road bridge, until 1982 when [[British Rail]] decided to construct a replacement platform 90 meters north, parallel to Peak Hill Gardens due to the retaining wall beginning to collapse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydenhamsociety.com/2011/09/sydenham-station-one-of-best-preserved-on-line/|title = Sydenham Station one of best preserved on line|publisher=Sydenham Society|year=2011|accessdate =21 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Big Four (British railway companies)|Big Four grouping]] led to [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway (SR)]] management until nationalistation in 1948. Between 1948 and 1982 Sydenham was part of the [[Southern Region of British Railways|Southern Region]] and following sectorisation, until privatisation, Sydenham became part of the [[Network SouthEast]] sector. Upon privatisation in May 1996, the station management passed to [[Connex South Central]]. Connex was stripped of the franchise due to poor financial management and in 2001, Govia South Central (Southern) took over the franchise and management of the station. Southern remained the sole train provider until 2010, when London Overground took over management of the station and began running trains as part of the [[East London Line]] extension.\n\nSydenham was the first station to serve the area, however, there are, or have been, five other stations in the Sydenham:\n* {{Stnlnk|Lower Sydenham}} on the [[Hayes Line]]\n* {{Stnlnk|Upper Sydenham}} on the now closed [[Crystal Palace railway station|Crystal Palace (High Level) line]]\n* {{Stnlnk|Sydenham Hill}}, {{Stnlnk|Penge East}} on the {{LUL stations|station=Victoria}} to [[Orpington]] line.\n\n==Station layout==\nLike all intermediate stations between New Cross Gate and Norwood Junction, Sydenham has two platforms, facing two (up and down slow) of the four tracks with the two fast tracks run between the two slow lines. There are three entrances - the ticket office on platform 2 from Sydenham Station Approach, entrance on platform 1 from Peak Hill Gardens and a gate on platform 2 which is not unlocked regularly. A locally owned small cafe named ''On The Hoof'' which also has locations at other stations on the line, is in the main station building.\n\n==Services==\n{{London Overground East London Line |width=360px |collapse=yes }}\n\nSydenham is served by 8 trains in each direction off peak, with additional Southern services at peak hours. London Overground operates 5 car trains while Southern operates 4-10 car trains throughout the day.\n\nOff Peak frequencies are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Platform\n! Frequency<br>(per hour)\n! Destination\n! Service Pattern\n! Operator\n! Line\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 1\n|rowspan=3| 4\n| [[Highbury & Islington station|Highbury & Islington]]\n|rowspan=2| All stations via<br> {{rws|Shoreditch High Street}}<ref name=\"ELL Times\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/highbury-islington-to-west-croydon-and-clapham-junction-timetable-may-2013.pdf| title = East & Inner South London Line timetable| publisher=[[Transport for London]]| year=2013| accessdate =26 August 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023011137/http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/highbury-islington-to-west-croydon-and-clapham-junction-timetable-may-2013.pdf| archivedate=23 October 2013}}</ref>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|- \n| {{rws|Dalston Junction}}\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n| [[London Bridge station|London Bridge]]\n| All stations<ref name=\"SN Metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/plan-your-journey/timetables/|title = Southern timetables|publisher=Southern|year=2013|accessdate =26 August 2013| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815144833/http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/plan-your-journey/timetables/| archivedate=15 August 2013}}</ref>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''      \n|-\n|rowspan=6| 2\n|rowspan=2| 4\n| {{rws|Crystal Palace}}\n| Next station<ref name=\"ELL Times\"/>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n| [[West Croydon station|West Croydon]]\n| All stations<ref name=\"ELL Times\"/>\n| London Overground\n| style=\"background:#ef7b10; color:white;\"| '''East London'''\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2\n| [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]]<br> (Mon-Sat)\n| All stations via {{rws|Clapham Junction}}<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| {{rws|Caterham}} (Mon-Sat)\n| All stations via [[East Croydon station|East Croydon]]<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| [[West Croydon station|West Croydon]]<br> (Peaks & Sun only)\n| Fast to {{rws|Norwood Junction}}<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|-\n| {{rws|Tattenham Corner}}<br> (Sun only)\n| All stations via [[East Croydon station|East Croydon]]<ref name=\"SN Metro\"/>\n| Southern\n| style=\"background:#4B0082; color:white;\"| '''Metro'''\n|}\n\n==Connections==\n[[London Buses]] routes [[London Buses route 122|122]], [[London Buses route 176|176]],  [[London Buses route 197|197]], [[London Buses route 202|202]] and [[London Buses route 450|450]] serve the station. While routes [[London Buses route 75|75]] and [[London Buses route 194|194]] run close by.\n\n==Lines==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rail|title=LOG}}\n{{s-line|system=LOG|line=East London|previous=Forest Hill|next=Crystal Palace|type=One|type2=Three|rowsmid=2|rows1=2}}\n{{s-line|system=LOG|line=East London|previous=Forest Hill|next=Penge West|type=One|type2=Four|hidemid=yes|hide1=yes}}\n{{rail insert}}\n{{rail line one to two|previous={{Stnlnk|Forest Hill}}|next1={{Stnlnk|Crystal Palace}}|next2={{Stnlnk|Penge West}} or {{stnlnk|Norwood Junction}}||route1=[[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]]<br><small>[[Crystal Palace Line]]|route2=[[Southern (train operating company)|Southern]]<br><small>[[Brighton Main Line]]|col=A7CE38}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sydenham railway station (London)}}\n*[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/SYD/details.html National Rail: Sydenham (SYD)]\n*[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/sjp/SYD/stationOverview.xhtml National Rail: Sydenham station plan]\n*[http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/station-information/SYD/ Southern: Sydenham page]\n*[http://www.southernrailway.com/your-journey/live-running-information/SYD/departures/ Southern:  Live departures, Sydenham]\n*{{gbmaprim|TQ3530071611|Maps and aerial photos}}\n\n{{Transport in London}}\n{{TSGN and SE Stations|Outer South=y|Caterham=y|FCC None=y|SE None=y}}\n{{London Overground navbox|Serving=y|ELL=y}}\n{{UK railway stations}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in the London Borough of Lewisham]]\n[[Category:Former London, Brighton and South Coast Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1839]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by London Overground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Southern]]\n[[Category:Sydenham, London]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sydenham_railway_station_(London)"}
{"title_page": "2002 World Snooker Championship", "text_new": "{{short description|Snooker tournament, held April/May 2002}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox Individual Snooker Tournament\n|tournament_name=2002 Embassy [[World Snooker Championship]]\n|logo=\n|dates=20 April\u20136 May 2002\n|venue=[[Crucible Theatre]]\n|location=[[Sheffield]]\n|country=[[England]]\n|organisation=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|WPBSA]]\n|format=[[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]] event\n|Total prize fund=[[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,615,770\n|winners_share=\u00a3260,000\n|highest_break={{flagicon|WAL}} [[Matthew Stevens]] (145)\n|winner={{flagicon|ENG}} [[Peter Ebdon]]\n|runner_up={{flagicon|SCO}} [[Stephen Hendry]]\n|score=18\u201317\n|previous=[[2001 World Snooker Championship|2001]]\n|next=[[2003 World Snooker Championship|2003]]}}\n\nThe '''2002 World Snooker Championship''' (also referred to as the '''2002 Embassy World Snooker Championship''' for the purposes of sponsorship) was a professional [[snooker]] tournament that took place from 20&nbsp;April to 6&nbsp;May 2002 at the [[Crucible Theatre]] in [[Sheffield]], England. It was the final [[Snooker world rankings|ranking]] event of the [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001\u201302 snooker season]]. This was the 26th consecutive year that the [[World Snooker Championship]] had been held at the Crucible, marking the 25th anniversary of the first staging of the event at this venue.\n\n[[Peter Ebdon]] won his first world title by defeating seven-time winner [[Stephen Hendry]] 18\u201317 in the final. Ebdon defeated [[Matthew Stevens]] 17\u201316 in the semi-finals, while Hendry defeated the defending champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 17\u201313 to reach the final. This was Hendry's ninth and last appearance in a World Championship final.  \n\nThere was a total of 65 [[century break]]s made during the tournament. The highest of the tournament was made by Stevens, who made a 145 in his quarter-final match. Hendry made a total of 16 centuries during the event, a record for any individual tournament. The championships were sponsored by cigarette manufacturer [[Embassy (cigarette)|Embassy]].\n\n==Tournament summary==\n* [[Steve Davis]] failed to qualify for the World Championship for the second year in a row, losing to Finland's [[Robin Hull]] 8\u201310 in the last round of qualifying at the [[Newport Centre (Wales)|Newport Centre]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Robin Hull profile (2002 World Snooker Championship) |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/worldchampionships2002/profiles/story_get.dor?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life/02/04/11/manual_150559.html |website=[[Sporting Life (British newspaper)|sportinglife.com]] |date=2002-06-14 |accessdate=11 May 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020614113933/http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/worldchampionships2002/profiles/story_get.dor?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life%2F02%2F04%2F11%2Fmanual_150559.html |archivedate=14 June 2002 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Future world champion [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] made his Crucible debut at this year's championship, losing 4\u201310 to [[Stephen Hendry]] in the first round.\n* [[Stuart Bingham]] narrowly missed out on a [[maximum break]] during his first-round match against [[Ken Doherty]], making it to the final pink.<ref>{{cite web |title=Snooker: Bingham falls short in maximum chase |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-84975437 |newspaper=[[Birmingham Post]] |via=[[Questia Online Library]] |date=2002-04-22 |accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n* World number one [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] was defeated 9\u201313 by world number 19 [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] in the second round of the competition.<ref name=BBC070404>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/3557783.stm |title=2002: Ebdon wins pulsating final |date=2004-04-07 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2019-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040515051256/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/3557783.stm |archive-date=15 May 2004 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Stephen Hendry reached his ninth World Championship final, beating the record of eight appearances in the final set by Steve Davis in the 1980s.\n* Referee [[John Williams (snooker referee)|John Williams]] presided over his tenth World Championship final. He retired from the game soon afterwards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/interactive/top_tens_story/0,25722,12284_6091752,00.html |title=Top 10 Crucible finals |work=[[Sky Sports]] |year=2010 |accessdate=19 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021004705/http://www.skysports.com/interactive/top_tens_story/0%2C25722%2C12284_6091752%2C00.html |archivedate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n* Ebdon's victory made him the first player to win both his semi-final and the final in deciding frames. In the semi-final, down 14\u201316 to [[Matthew Stevens]], Ebdon cleared up under pressure, after Stevens ran out of position needing just one more red to win the frame and the match. Ebdon then followed with breaks of 138 and 55 to win the match 17\u201316.<ref name=Guardian050502>{{cite news |title=Ebdon edges through after thriller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/05/snooker.theobserver |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2002-05-05 |accessdate=9 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509221258/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/05/snooker.theobserver |archive-date=9 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Hendry took the record for century breaks in a World Championship, as his 16 centuries bettered the previous record total of 14 set by [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] in 1998.<ref name=\"cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Final===\nThe final between Peter Ebdon (seventh in the [[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|world rankings]]) and Stephen Hendry (ranked fifth) was a repeat of the [[1996 World Snooker Championship|1996 World Championship]] final where Hendry had defeated Ebdon 18\u201312 to gain his sixth world title.<ref name=Guardian050502 /> Over eight million viewers watched the 2002 final in the expectation of Hendry winning his eighth world title.<ref name=BBC070404 /><ref name=BBC180203>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1969709.stm |title=Ebdon wins Crucible thriller |date=2003-02-18 |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2019-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060209125812/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1969709.stm |archive-date=9 February 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nEbdon took the first four frames of the match to lead 4\u20130 at the first mid-session interval, but Hendry pulled back the next four frames to end the first session tied at 4\u20134. By the end of the second session, Ebdon was again four frames ahead at 10\u20136, but Hendry fought back and levelled the score at the end of the third session, 12\u201312.<ref name=BBC180203 /><ref name=Guardian070502>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/07/snooker.worldsnookerchampionship2002 |title=A night on the sofa with Peter Ebdon |first=Sean |last=Ingle |date=2002-05-07 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2019-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013085000/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/07/snooker.worldsnookerchampionship2002 |archive-date=13 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHendry made a strong start to the final session, taking the lead for the first time with breaks of 63, 55 and 38, to put him 14\u201312 ahead. Ebdon won the next two frames to draw level at 14\u201314, after Hendry missed a relatively simple red in the 28th frame. Hendry then compiled a break of 58 in frame 29, to lead 15\u201314, but Ebdon took three of the next four frames with breaks of 73, 111 and 85 to move ahead 17\u201316.<ref name=BBC180203 /><ref name=Guardian070502 />\n\nPoised to win the championship, Ebdon was 52\u201327 up in frame 34 when he missed a straight pot on the black on its spot, allowing Hendry to clear the colours and level the match at 17\u201317.<ref name=BBC070404 /><ref name=Guardian080502>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/08/comment.worldsnookerchampionship2002 |title=Cometh the hour, came the man |first=Clive |last=Everton |date=2002-05-08 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2019-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927132356/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/08/comment.worldsnookerchampionship2002 |archive-date=27 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> This was the second time that Hendry had been taken to a deciding frame in the World Championship final<ref name=BBC180203 /> (his first being in [[1995 World Snooker Championship|1995]] when he defeated Jimmy White in the 35th frame).<ref name=Independent080502 /> Hendry was the first to score in the decider, just seven points, before Ebdon compiled a break of 59.<ref name=BBC070404 /><ref name=BBC180203 /> Then with just four reds remaining on the table,<ref name=Guardian080502 /> Hendry potted the cue ball while attempting to play a snooker, giving Ebdon his chance to take the frame and win the match 18\u201317.<ref name=BBC070404 /><ref name=Independent080502>{{cite news |title=Snooker: Ebdon and the trophy he tried to throw away |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/snooker-ebdon-and-the-trophy-he-tried-to-throw-away-9252975.html |first=Nick |last=Harris |date=2002-05-08 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=9 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510050556/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/snooker-ebdon-and-the-trophy-he-tried-to-throw-away-9252975.html |archive-date=10 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWith his win, Ebdon received a cheque for \u00a3260,000 and moved up to third place in the end-of-season world rankings (behind Ronnie O'Sullivan and Mark Williams).<ref name=Guardian080502 /><ref name=Independent080502 /> In a post-match interview, he said \"It's what I have been working for and dreaming about for the last 17 years... I wasn't ready to win it six years ago, but I've improved as a player and as a person\".<ref name=Guardian080502 /> ''The Guardian'''s Sean Ingle described the final as \"one of the sporting highlights of the year.\"<ref name=Guardian070502 />\n\nMany commentators had been expecting Hendry to take his eighth world title.<ref name=Guardian070502 /> He ultimately blamed his defeat on nerves and poor concentration, but also conceded that Ebdon was a stronger player than he had been in their previous world final encounter in 1996.<ref name=Independent080502 /> This was Hendry's last appearance in a World Championship final. His defeat effectively signalled the start of his decline as a major force in the game of snooker; he reached his last ranking final four years later at the [[2006 UK Championship]], where he again lost to Peter Ebdon.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/all-sports/snookers-greatest-has-gone-too-soon_sto4706796/story.shtml |title=Snooker's greatest has gone too soon |first=Desmond |last=Kane |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=2012-05-02 |accessdate=2019-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230084801/https://www.eurosport.co.uk/all-sports/snookers-greatest-has-gone-too-soon_sto4706796/story.shtml |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Prize fund==\nThe breakdown of prize money for this year is shown below:<ref name=\"Global Snooker\">{{cite web |title=World Championship 2002 |url=http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-2002.asp |website=global-snooker.com |accessdate=24 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310184004/http://www.global-snooker.com/professional-snooker-tournaments-archive-world-championship-2002.asp |archive-date=10 March 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Downer |first=Chris |title=Crucible Almanac |year=2012 |pages=130}}</ref>\n{{Col-begin|width=70%}}\n{{Col-break|width=50%}}\n*Winner: [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]260,000\n*Runner-up: \u00a3152,000\n*Semi-final: \u00a376,000\n*Quarter-final: \u00a338,000\n*Last 16: \u00a321,000\n*Last 32: \u00a314,500\n*Last 48: \u00a311,000\n*Last 64: \u00a36,825\n{{Col-break|width=50%}}\n*Last 80: \u00a35,500\n*Last 96: \u00a34,150\n*Last 128: \u00a31,185\n*Stage one highest break: \u00a32,250\n*Stage two highest break: \u00a320,000\n*Stage one maximum break: \u00a35,000\n*Stage two maximum break: \u00a3147,000\n*Total: \u00a31,615,770\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== Main draw ==\nShown below are the results for each round. The numbers in parentheses beside some of the players are their seeding ranks (each championship has 16 seeds and 16 qualifiers).<ref name=\"Global Snooker\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=World Snooker results and reports |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1959667.stm |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=24 March 2011 |date=6 May 2002 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127091211/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1959667.stm |archive-date=27 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Downer |first=Chris |title=Crucible Almanac |year=2012 |pages=54\u201355}}</ref>\n{{World Snooker Championship Rounds\n<!--Date-Place/Player 1/Score 1/Player 2/Score 2 -->\n<!-- LAST 32 -->\n<!--Match1  -->\n|20 April<ref>{{cite news |last=Chowdhury |first=Saj |title=O'Sullivan eases through |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1941542.stm |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=24 March 2011 |date=20 April 2002 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306041744/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1941542.stm |archive-